							<div class="rowTxt">
							
							
							
								<p class="newsHead">Mortgage Fraud</p>
								<p class="newsDate">Aug&nbsp;2009</p>
								<p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 11pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Tahoma"><span style="mso-spacerun: yes"></span></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">In a depressed market, problems are revealed in the same way that a receding tide exposes shipwrecks on a seabed. In many cases the issues emerging have simply gone undiscovered during the buoyant market in the last few years and the marked increase in large-scale mortgage fraud and negligence being uncovered is a direct effect of the downturn. </span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span></p><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">T</span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">he amount of mortgage fraud cases being uncovered by lenders and their solicitors has shot up in the past few years. The </span><stockticker /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">SRA</span></stockticker /><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"> reported an increase of 11 per cent from 2007 to 2008 and the Association of Chief Police Officers estimated mortgage fraud in 2007 at £700m. We expect this figure to continue to increase significantly for at least the next two years.</span></p><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Whilst the market was high, more opportunity was available for negligent and deliberate over or under valuations, undisclosed incentives, direct deposits and back-to-back sales to go through under the radar. The increase in buy-to-let mortgages and new-build flats provided fertile ground for the mortgage fraudster and given the growth in this market over the last ten years, the level of mortgage fraud yet to be identified in this area is likely to increase significantly.</span></p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Whereas buy-to-let investors were few and wealthy in the late 80s, this time round significantly more people entered the market, along with new lenders and new mortgage products.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Borrowers have managed to purchase properties without investing any of their own money and indeed in some circumstances, have received money from the lender because of over inflated purchase prices. Whilst the vast majority of conveyancers have been careful to investigate and report unusual features of a transaction to their lender client, there are those who (even where not fraudulent themselves), have failed significantly in their duty to report matters such as back to back transactions, direct deposits and related parties, despite the guidance given in the Law Society’s practice note (formerly the “Green Card”) on mortgage fraud.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span></span></p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">Many of the frauds have been uncovered as the number of repossessions rise.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Lenders are often first alerted to the possibility of fraud only by an unexpectedly high loss suffered on sale. Mortgage books need to be reviewed in detail as increasingly property developers, brokers, solicitors and surveyors have been revealed to be working in collaboration: deals can appear to be backed by professional surveyors and solicitors and involve apparently respectable customers and brokers. Where one firm or name is uncovered as a participant in a fraud, a lender’s records need to be reviewed to establish if other transactions may also be affected.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>Cases where the charge has never been registered need also to be investigated to understand the reason why: is there good reason for the delay or does the lack of registration indicate there is something “unusual” about the transaction?</span></p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">In cases where the repossession valuation is significantly lower than expected, lenders and their lawyers need to revisit the original valuation in light of the time elapsed, to establish any discrepancies or unusual movements in price. Where unusual features are established, retrospective evidence of value needs to be obtained. Once the cases have been identified, insurers need to be put on notice and letters of claim sent under the Professional Negligence Pre Action Protocol.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span></span></p><p /><p /><p class="MsoNormal" style="MARGIN: 0cm 0cm 0pt; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%"><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial"></span><span style="FONT-SIZE: 9pt; COLOR: black; LINE-HEIGHT: 150%; FONT-FAMILY: Arial">The headlines, continue to highlight multi-million pound mortgage fraud cases being uncovered. Surveyors, solicitors and bank officials were arrested in the £40m defrauding of Bradford &amp; Bingley in a case involving 500 properties. A write down of £56m of outstanding loan balances was recorded against Allied Irish Banks. The Serious Fraud Office said further financial institutions were likely to have been deceived by the suspects, so further loss is likely to be reported. Lenders are, of course, much more vigilant now and the sharp reduction in the number and ease of availability of mortgages will inevitably mean that mortgage fraud cases become far less frequent in the future. At the moment however, the best that lenders can do is trawl through their existing books to identify where they have already been victims and take remedial action as soon as possible.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span>In light of the scale of the problem and the potential issues with establishing and securing cover with the defendant’s insurers for these cases, it is imperative that lenders take a proactive approach to uncovering fraud. Recovery will become more difficult as time passes: doing nothing at this stage is therefore not an option.<span style="mso-spacerun: yes">  </span></span></p><p /><p /><p /></p>
								
								
								<img src="../../content/cms/uploads/large/21313.jpg"  />
								
